{"cursor":"22689","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nAn 'ion' is an atom or molecule in which the total number of electrons is not\nequal to the total number of protons, giving the atom a net positive or negative\nelectrical charge.\n\nIons can be created by both chemical and physical means. In chemical terms, if a\nneutral atom loses one or more electrons, it has a net positive charge and is\nknown as an cation. If an atom gains electrons, it has a net negative charge and\nis known as an anion. An ion consisting of a single atom is an atomic or\nmonatomic ion; if it consists of two or more atoms, it is a molecular or\npolyatomic ion.\n\nIn the case of physical ionization of a medium, such as a gas, what are known as\n\"ion pairs\" are created by ion impact, and each pair consists of a free electron\nand a positive ion.\n","linknr":471,"url":"cationic","recorded":1362670568,"links":103,"instances":["physics_articles","physics","particle_radiation","chemistry"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Ions|","Physical chemistry","Charge carriers"],"headings":["Anions and cations","History of discovery","Characteristics","Related technology","Chemistry","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fc/Padlock-silver.svg/20px-Padlock-silver.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/29/Ions.svg/390px-Ions.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ac/Main_tycho_remnant_full.jpg/200px-Main_tycho_remnant_full.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Ion_chamber_operation.gif/300px-Ion_chamber_operation.gif","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a